<chapter id="lvlcs"><title id="tvlcs">The VideoLAN Channel Server</title>


<para>
The VideoLAN Channel Server is useful when you want to stream multiple
videos at the same time and enable the clients to change channel (i.e.
switching from one stream to another) easily without typing IP adresses,
but just using the interface and selecting a channel number
</para>

<sect1><title>Installing the VideoLAN Channel Server</title>

<para>Note: The miniVLCS is only available for Linux.</para>
<para>Note: You don't have to change anything to vls. You are going to
install the mini VideoLAN Channel Server (miniVLCS) and configure it.
You can install miniVLCS on the same machine as vls.<para>
<para>Download the latest version of miniVLCS from the Network download
page.</para>
<para>Install-it:</para>
<para><screen>
   <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> tar xvzf miniVLCS-version.tar.gz</userinput>
   <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> cd miniVLCS-version</userinput>
   <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> make</userinput>
</screen></para>
<para>It creates an executable program names vlcs.</para>

</sect1>

<sect1><title>Configuring the VideoLAN Channel Server</title>

<para>Edit the <filename>vlcs.conf</filename> configuration file : (a sample vlcs.conf is given)</para>
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>one line per channel</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>lines are considered raw data and sent directly to the
client (ex: I: nostream)<para></listitem>
<listitem><para>lines beginning by I: are 'dummy' channel programs to tell
the vlc there is nothing in this channel (which should be the case of
channel 0)</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>each lines contains  what you would type on the
command line for the vlc</para>
<para>    for example :</para>
<para>        for broadcast : udp:192.168.10.12@192.168.255.255</para>
<para>        for multicast : udp:@238.2.12.42</para>
<para>        for VOD : http://myhost.mydomain.com/video.mpeg</para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>

</sect1>

<sect1><title>Run the Videolan Channel Server</title>

<para>As normal user, type:</para>
<para><screen><prompt>%</prompt><userinput> ./vlcs</userinput></screen></para>
<para>For production, you should run the program in a screen, so that
you can detach-it and reattach-it:</para>
<para><screen><prompt>%</prompt><userinput> screen ./vlcs</userinput></screen></para>

</sect1>

<sect1><title>Configure vlc to use the channel service</title>

<para>The simplest solution is to use the interface of vlc: click on
"Net", select "Channel server" and enter the miniVLCS' IP address or DNS
name.</para>
<para>Then, you see a new section "Network Channel" on the interface.
Select the channel of your choice and click on "Go!".</para>

</sect1>
